  📝 Generating Slide 4: Architecture of a First Generation Computer

--- [DEBUG] NARRATION LLM OUTPUT ---
Notice how the vacuum tubes, the heart of these early machines, are densely packed to form the central processing unit. These tubes act as switches, controlling electrical signals to perform calculations, but they generate a lot of heat and consume significant power.  

The memory units, often magnetic drums or delay lines, are shown here as separate blocks. They store data and instructions temporarily, but their capacity and speed were very limited compared to modern standards, which affected overall performance.  

Input and output devices like punched cards and paper tape readers are positioned on the periphery. These devices allowed users to feed data into the computer and receive printed results, reflecting the mechanical nature of data handling at the time.  

The control unit, highlighted here, orchestrates the operation of the entire system by directing the flow of data between memory, processing units, and input/output devices. Its design was complex due to the reliance on vacuum tubes and mechanical components.
