🎬 [Batch Gen] Subtopic: First Generation (1940-1959): Vacuum Tubes & Electromechanical Computers | Slides 5-6 of 7
  📝 Generating Slide 5: Evolution Timeline: 1940-1959 First Generation Milestones

--- [DEBUG] NARRATION LLM OUTPUT ---
During the first generation of computers, from 1940 to 1959, vacuum tubes replaced mechanical switches, allowing machines to process data electronically for the first time. These tubes acted as both amplifiers and switches, significantly increasing computing speed compared to earlier electromechanical devices.

The ENIAC, one of the earliest and most famous computers of this era, used over 17,000 vacuum tubes, making it massive but groundbreaking. It demonstrated how electronic components could perform complex calculations much faster than previous technologies, setting a foundation for future computers.

Following ENIAC, the EDVAC introduced the stored-program concept, which was a major leap forward in flexibility and efficiency. Around the same time, the UNIVAC I became the first commercially available computer, showing how this technology could move beyond research labs into business and government applications.

Although these machines were large, power-hungry, and prone to overheating, they marked the beginning of the digital age. Their limitations inspired innovations that led directly to the development of smaller, faster, and more reliable second-generation computers.
