  📝 Generating Slide 6: Vacuum Tubes vs Electromechanical Components

--- [DEBUG] NARRATION LLM OUTPUT ---
Vacuum tubes were the primary electronic components in early computers, enabling much faster processing speeds than electromechanical parts, which relied on physical movement and were inherently slower. This speed advantage was crucial in handling complex calculations more efficiently.

However, vacuum tubes were less reliable because they generated a lot of heat and were prone to frequent failures. Electromechanical components, while slower, tended to be more durable and could operate longer without breaking down, making them somewhat more dependable in certain contexts.

In terms of size, vacuum tube computers were massive, often filling entire rooms, due to the large number of tubes and cooling systems required. Electromechanical machines were also bulky but often even larger because of the mechanical parts and moving components they used.

Power consumption was significantly higher in vacuum tube systems, which needed substantial electricity to operate and cool the tubes. Electromechanical computers consumed less power but sacrificed speed and efficiency, highlighting the trade-offs engineers faced during this era.
